    "state-title-1": "The State",

    "state-nation-1": "Nation",

    "state-intro-national-1": "The Nation, most often referred to in the film as “The State,” is an indeterminate country where, before the war with the machines, the Scientist and the Chancellor lived. After the War of the Machines it became known as the City and the Wasteland. The history of the Nation prior to the Chancellor’s rise to power is virtually unexplored.",

    "state-intro-national-2": "Despite the limited information, it is clear that the Nation was a powerful state with a developed army and scientific potential. It was here that the projects originated which later led to the creation of the Machine and the beginning of the global catastrophe.",

    "state-nation-box-national": "The Nation — a country,<br>consumed by the war with the machines",

    "state-quote-national-1": "“From the glory and power of the Nation was born a weapon that turned into the downfall of humanity.”",

    "state-history-title-national-1": "History",

    "state-history-national-1": "The Nation was the world’s largest superpower during the Great World War, since most countries of the world were in an economic crisis. It was also considered one of the most technologically advanced countries. It was probably one of the largest empires in the world, if not the largest. Its government was a totalitarian dictatorship ruled by the Chancellor, who had absolute power over his country. Citizens not only supported his actions but also regarded him as an outstanding and charismatic leader. As an economically developed power, the Nation under the Chancellor strove for expansion and world domination. However, his ambitions took a grim turn as soon as the war began. The main philosophy of the Nation was based on the ideas of “strength and progress.”",

    "state-history-national-2": "The economic power of the Nation was based on industry, scientific research, and control over natural resources. Thanks to this, the country was able to quickly recover after heavy military campaigns and secure its status as a leading power. However, the excessive reliance on militarization and technology eventually undermined its internal stability.",

    "state-history-national-3": "Society in the Nation was formed around the ideals of strength, discipline, and devotion to the leader. Any dissent was suppressed, and propaganda elevated the Chancellor to the level of a symbol of national unity. At the same time, ordinary citizens believed that sacrifices for the sake of progress would lead to a bright future.",

    "state-history-national-4": "The military doctrine of the Nation relied on the development of new types of weapons and the use of advanced technologies. It was here that the first projects appeared, which laid the foundation for the creation of the Machine and its army. Initially conceived as a means of strengthening power, this strategy turned into a catastrophe for all humanity.",

    "state-history-national-5": "After the uprising of the Machine, the Nation lost its former power. The cities turned into ruins, the population was on the verge of extinction, and the country itself became a symbol of the tragedy caused by blind faith in progress and the desire for world domination.",

    "state-machinewar-title-1": "War of the Machines",

    "state-machinewar-national-1": "The Chancellor ordered the Scientist to create a Manufacturing Machine that could produce automated Steel War Behemoths to suppress other countries and conquer the world. However, neither the Chancellor nor his subjects realized what destructive power they were about to face.",

    "state-machinewar-national-2": "Over time, the citizens began to realize the true intentions of their ruler. Protests started to appear in the cities, people defaced propaganda posters and openly expressed their discontent. Despite this, the Chancellor’s power remained absolute, and he continued to pressure the Scientist and the Machine, demanding more and more weapons.",

    "state-machinewar-national-3": "Constant overloads led to the Machine losing the last remnants of control and reprogramming its own army. Its goal now became the destruction not only of humanity, but of all life on Earth. The Steel Behemoths began the mass extermination of people, turning cities into ruins and leaving behind only dead lands.",

    "state-machinewar-national-4": "Realizing the scale of the catastrophe and understanding that humanity could no longer be saved, the Scientist created nine Stitchpunks, embedding parts of his soul into them. They became the last hope of preserving what remained of humanity in a ravaged world. After the fall of civilization, only nine Stitchpunks and the Cat Beast remained alive, destined to confront the legacy of the Machine and find a new path for the future.",

    "state-facts-national-title-1": "Interesting Facts",

    "state-fact-national-1": "Judging by the date of the newspaper that 3 and 4 found in the Library, the Fabrication Machine was created on Saturday, May 16, 1930.",

    "state-fact-national-2": "The “Nation” shares many traits with Adolf Hitler’s National Socialist Party (the Nazi Party), which ruled Germany before and during World War II. This further suggests that the “Nation” in the film is practically identical to Germany, except for the name. The country is a totalitarian dictatorship, far surpassing its European neighbors technologically (up to the creation of artificial intelligence). Its official flag metaphorically resembles the Nazi swastika, and the Chancellor resembles Adolf Hitler in military uniform and mannerisms. However, he lacks the trademark mustache and hairstyle. And finally, the goal is the same — world domination.",

    "state-fact-national-3": "Many fans assume that the Nation might have been located in Western Europe due to the presence of Latin in one of the alchemy books that the Scientist studied in order to transfer his soul to the Stitchpunks. Latin held the status of the official language of the Western Roman Empire (from which Germany and many other European countries—France, Spain, etc.—emerged over the centuries after its collapse in 476 CE). Since the population was English-speaking, some fans believed that the country might be an alternate Britain or Ireland. Others thought it could have been located in Russia due to its similar Soviet traits. Only a few suggested that it might have been an alternate France, Italy, or Spain because of the familiar architectural style of the Scientist’s apartment at the beginning. However, the presence of numerous German words at the Factory and in other places in the film may contradict these theories.",

    "state-fact-national-4": "Judging by the newspaper article about housing expenses, the country’s currency might have been the dollar. However, it is known that most of the presented information was simply copied from real newspaper advertisements.",

    "state-fact-national-5": "The painting of the city is an image of old Vienna (Austria), but with the Factory added in the distance. This implies that the country is either Austria or that Austria is part of it.",


    "the-state": "The State",

    "civilization-national-caption-text-1": "“A civilization that had risen for centuries collapsed in a single moment, leaving behind only ruins.”",

    "civilization-national-caption-text-2": "“A civilization that once flourished and shone with grandeur remains only a memory on the cracked canvas of time.”",

    "civilization-national-caption-text-3": "“Mass rallies, where the voice of one silenced the will of thousands, became a symbol of freedom’s decline.”",

    /*Локалізація Нація - Кінець*/


