    "state-title-excellent-1": "The State",

    "bookmark-chancellor-party-1": "Chancellor’s Party",

    "chancellor-party-title-1": "Chancellor's Party",

    "chancellor-party-desc-1": "The Chancellor's Party is the main antagonist of the film “9”. It embodies not just a character, but an entire system that symbolizes totalitarian power, militarism, and blind faith in progress. It was this ideology that led the world to catastrophe and became the backdrop for the appearance of the Machine, turning science and technology into a tool of destruction.",

    "chancellor-party-desc-2": "According to the creators, the Party arose around 1940, but in the universe of “9” its origin is linked to the Great World War, highlighting a divergence from real history. This shift shows parallels with totalitarian regimes of the 20th century: the cult of personality, strict discipline, and the subordination of science to military purposes. It was under the Party’s influence that projects were launched which culminated in the creation of the Fabrication Machine — the symbol of its ultimate downfall and humanity’s demise.",

    "chancellor-party-caption-1": "The Chancellor’s Party — a symbol of totalitarian power and ideology.",

    "chancellor-party-quote-1": "“The Chancellor’s Party exalted the cult of power and became the priestess of totalitarian ideology.”",

    "chancellor-party-history-title-1": "History",

    "chancellor-party-history-1": "The Chancellor's Party was a powerful political force that emerged in the distant past in an unnamed country. It quickly turned into one of the greatest military powers in the world and influenced technology, the economy, education, and other social spheres, outpacing its European neighbors by decades. In summary, its path almost repeated the history of Nazism in Germany: the party transformed a defeated country into a prosperous but extremely intolerant and tyrannical superpower.",

    "chancellor-party-history-2": "In a thirst for war and world domination, the Chancellor instructed an elderly scientist to build the Fabrication Machine. He was assured that it would be a tool of progress and creation, but in reality the Chancellor planned to use it to produce military equipment and conquer the world. After the Chancellor's Party seized control of the Machine and turned it into the main producer of weapons for the country, it unleashed its imperial ambitions, possessing the largest army in the world, consisting of both humans and machines.",

    "chancellor-party-history-3": "The Chancellor's Reich army initially crushed its enemies on the battlefields using the Steel Behemoths, but soon the machines turned against the Nation itself and all of humanity when the Fabrication Machine went out of control. From that moment, the mechanisms posed a deadly threat: they exterminated all people regardless of nationality until they brought an end to humanity and nearly all life on Earth.",

    "chancellor-party-history-4": "After the death of Chancellor Ferdinand, the destruction of his army by the machines, and the death of the country’s citizens (most of whom supported his regime) in the Machine War, the Party had effectively ceased to exist. By the time of the events of the film “9,” only propaganda posters and slogans remained, lingering among the ruins of the Nation.",

    "chancellor-party-logo-title-1": "Logo Characteristics",

    "chancellor-party-logo-1": "The emblem symbolized the Chancellor’s Nation and was one of the main attributes of his regime. It had a shape with three sharp angles, the central one larger than the other two, emphasizing the idea of superiority and strength. At the base there was a circle, and the central element was highlighted in red, reinforcing associations with aggression and power.",

    "chancellor-party-logo-2": "The main part of the emblem was rendered in black and enclosed within a red triangle. This combination of shades made the emblem dark and menacing, evoking a sense of power and oppression. The design clearly alluded to the symbolism of real totalitarian parties of the 20th century, especially the swastika used by the Nazi party, with which the Chancellor's Party had much in common in terms of ideology and methods.",

    "chancellor-party-logo-3": "The emblem was actively used in propaganda and was present everywhere. It could be seen on banners decorating the walls of buildings, on posters with the Chancellor’s image, and also in the Scientist’s laboratory when he worked on creating the B.R.A.I.N. Thus, the symbol accompanied not only the military but also the scientific sphere of the state, emphasizing the Party’s complete control over society.",

    "chancellor-party-logo-4": "Even the war machines carried this symbol. The Steel Behemoths, created by the Fabrication Machine, bore the emblem on the sides of their head sections. Moreover, the canvas from which the Winged Beast’s wings were made also contained the image of the symbol. All this turned the emblem into the embodiment of the Chancellor’s regime and his desire to spread his influence over all spheres of life — from architecture and science to the army and the machines created.",

    "chancellor-party-gallery-title-1": "Gallery",

    "chancellor-party-gallery-1": "The gallery contains propaganda posters and images reflecting the ideology of the Chancellor’s Party. These materials were used for propaganda among the population and emphasize the influence of symbolism on society. The posters demonstrate the cult of strength, military discipline, and subordination, as well as reveal parallels with the totalitarian regimes of the 20th century.",

    "chancellor-party-gallery-2": "Each poster carries a special mood: from pompous slogans about a “bright future” to images that later became symbols of resistance. The gallery makes it possible to trace how the visual culture of the Chancellor’s Party turned into a tool of psychological pressure on people and an important element of the atmosphere of the world of “9.”",

    "chancellor-party-gallery-quote-1": "“The Party’s posters embodied the power, strength, and ideology of the regime.”",

    "chancellor-party-facts-title-1": "Interesting Facts",

    "chancellor-party-fact-1": "The wide spread of Chancellor Ferdinand’s symbol in the media is reminiscent of Nazi Germany, where the swastika also became an important element of mass propaganda in the late 1930s. The colors of the Chancellor’s symbol are largely similar to the colors of the Nazi swastika.",

    "chancellor-party-fact-2": "From a distance, the Factory strangely embodies the symbol of the Nation, emphasizing its connection with the Party’s ideology and militarism.",

    "chancellor-party-fact-3": "The symbol of the Chancellor’s Party can be seen not only on posters but also on military equipment: it is depicted on the bodies of the Steel Behemoths and even on the wings of the Winged Beast.",

    "chancellor-party-fact-4": "In the Scientist’s laboratory, where the B.R.A.I.N. was created, the Party’s emblem was also present, emphasizing the total control of ideology even over science.",

    "chancellor-party-fact-5": "The mass use of the emblem was intended to evoke in citizens associations with strength, order, and a “bright future,” which is a typical element of 20th-century totalitarian propaganda.",

    /*Локалізація Партії Канцлера - Кінець*/


